      "## the very short science",
      "Your autonomic nervous system has two main branches: the sympathetic (mobilizing, fight-or-flight) and the parasympathetic (resting, digesting, connecting). A regulated nervous system flows fluidly between them. A dysregulated one gets stuck — usually in chronic sympathetic activation (anxiety, irritability, insomnia) or in dorsal shutdown (numbness, depression, dissociation).",
      "Polyvagal theory, developed by Stephen Porges, adds a third state: the ventral vagal, associated with social connection and safety. Most regulation practices are really practices for spending more time in ventral vagal, and recovering faster when you leave it.",
      "## what dysregulation feels like",
      "You might know it as: a chest that won't unclench, jaw tension you only notice when you stop, sleep that doesn't restore, snapping at people you love, the inability to enjoy things you used to enjoy, a sense of urgency that has no clear source. None of these are character flaws. They are signals.",
      "## the practices that work",
      "**Breath, slowed and lengthened.** The simplest intervention. Inhale for four counts, exhale for six or eight. The longer exhale activates the vagus nerve and signals safety. Three minutes is enough to shift your state.",
      "**Cold water on the face.** Splash cold water on your cheeks and around your eyes, or hold a cold compress there for thirty seconds. This triggers the mammalian dive reflex and lowers heart rate quickly. Useful for acute anxiety spikes.",
      "**Humming, singing, gargling.** The vagus nerve runs through the throat. Anything that gently vibrates that area — humming a song while you make breakfast, gargling water for thirty seconds — provides direct vagal stimulation.",
      "**Slow walking outside.** Twenty minutes, no podcast, no phone. Let your eyes do panoramic scanning of the horizon. This signals to your nervous system that there is no immediate threat, which most of us haven't told our bodies in years.",
